SIMPLE: rove
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rove
<hw>Rove</hw> <pr>(r⟦omac⟧v)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[perhaps fr. or
akin to <ets>reeve</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To draw through an eye
or aperture.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To draw out into flakes; to card, as wool.</def>
<rj><au>Jamieson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To twist slightly; to bring together, as slivers of
wool or cotton, and twist slightly before spinning.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rove</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rove
<hw>Rove</hw> <pr>(r⟦omac⟧v)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
copper washer upon which the end of a nail is clinched in boat
building.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A roll or sliver of wool or cotton drawn out and
slighty twisted, preparatory to further process; a roving.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rove</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Rove
<hw>Rove</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Roved</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Roving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. D. <ets>rooven</ets> to rob;
akin to E. <ets>reave</ets>. See <er>Reave</er>, <er>Rob</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To practice robbery on the seas; to wander about on the
seas in piracy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Hakluyt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, to wander; to ramble; to rauge; to go, move,
or pass without certain direction in any manner, by sailing, walking,
riding, flying, or otherwise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For who has power to walk has power to <qex>rove</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Archery)</fld> <def>To shoot at rovers; hence, to
shoot at an angle of elevation, not at point-blank (rovers usually being
beyond the point-blank range).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fair Venus' son, that with thy cruel dart⟦br⟧
At that good knight so cunningly didst <qex>rove</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To wander; roam; range; ramble stroll.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rove</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Rove
<hw>Rove</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To wander over or
through.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Roving</qex> the field, I chanced⟦br⟧
A goodly tree far distant to behold.</q> <rj><qau>milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To plow into ridges by turning the earth of two
furrows together.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rove</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Rove
<hw>Rove</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of wandering; a
ramble.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In thy nocturnal <qex>rove</qex> one moment halt.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Rove beetle</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of
numerous species of beetles of the family <fam>Staphylinidae</fam>,
having short elytra beneath which the wings are folded transversely.
They are rapid runners, and seldom fly.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rover</ent>⟦br⟧
